# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tpm-module
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] In computer security, a **chain of trust** is established by validating each component of hardware and software from the end entity up to the root certificate.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] It is intended to ensure that only trusted software and hardware can be used while still retaining flexibility.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] A chain of trust is designed to allow multiple users to create and use the software on the system, which would be more difficult if all the keys were stored directly in hardware.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] It starts with hardware that will only boot from software that is digitally signed (bootloader).
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] The signing authority will only sign boot programs that enforce security, such as only running programs that are themselves signed, or only allowing signed code to have access to certain features of the machine.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] This process may continue for several layers.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] This process results in a chain of trust.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] The final software can be trusted to have certain properties because if it had been illegally modified its signature would be invalid, and the previous software would not have executed it.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] The previous software can be trusted, because it, in turn, would not have been loaded if its signature had been invalid.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] The trustworthiness of each layer is guaranteed by the one before, back to the trust anchor.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] It would be possible to have the hardware check the suitability (signature) for every single piece of software.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] However, this would not produce the flexibility that a "chain" provides.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] In a chain, any given link can be replaced with a different version to provide different properties, without having to go all the way back to the trust anchor.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] This use of multiple layers is an application of a general technique to improve scalability and is analogous to the use of multiple certificates in a certificate chain.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] In computer security, digital certificates are verified using a chain of trust.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] The trust anchor for the digital certificate is the root certificate authority (CA).
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] The certificate hierarchy is a structure of certificates that allows individuals to verify the validity of a certificate's issuer.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] Certificates are issued and signed by certificates that reside higher in the certificate hierarchy, so the validity and trustworthiness of a given certificate is determined by the corresponding validity of the certificate that signed it.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] The chain of trust of a certificate chain is an ordered list of certificates, containing an end-user subscriber certificate and intermediate certificates (that represents the intermediate CA), that enables the receiver to verify that the sender and all intermediate certificates are trustworthy.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] This process is best described in the page *Intermediate certificate authority*.
[src:tpm-module/chain-of-trust] See also X.509 certificate chains for a description of these concepts in a widely used standard for digital certificates.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:tpm-module/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:tpm-module/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:tpm-module/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing proponents such as International Data Corporation, the Enterprise Strategy Group and Endpoint Technologies Associates state that the technology will make computers safer, less prone to viruses and malware, and thus more reliable from an end-user perspective.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] They also state that Trusted Computing will allow computers and servers to offer improved computer security over that which is currently available.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Opponents often state that this technology will be used primarily to enforce digital rights management policies (imposed restrictions to the owner) and not to increase computer security.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Chip manufacturers Intel and AMD, hardware manufacturers such as HP and Dell, and operating system providers such as Microsoft include Trusted Computing in their products if enabled.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Army requires that every new PC it purchases comes with a Trusted Platform Module (TPM).
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] As of July 3, 2007, so does virtually the entire United States Department of Defense.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The endorsement key is a 2048-bit RSA public and private key pair that is created randomly on the chip at manufacture time and cannot be changed.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The private key never leaves the chip, while the public key is used for attestation and for encryption of sensitive data sent to the chip, as occurs during the TPM_TakeOwnership command.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The TPM should be designed to make the extraction of this key by hardware analysis hard, but tamper resistance is not a strong requirement.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Memory curtaining extends common memory protection techniques to provide full isolation of sensitive areas of memory—for example, locations containing cryptographic keys.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Even the operating system does not have full access to curtained memory.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The exact implementation details are vendor specific.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Sealed storage protects private information by binding it to platform configuration information including the software and hardware being used.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] This means the data can be released only to a particular combination of software and hardware.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Sealed storage can be used for DRM enforcing.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] For example, users who keep a song on their computer that has not been licensed to be listened will not be able to play it.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Currently, a user can locate the song, listen to it, and send it to someone else, play it in the software of their choice, or back it up (and in some cases, use circumvention software to decrypt it).
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Alternatively, the user may use software to modify the operating system's DRM routines to have it leak the song data once, say, a temporary license was acquired.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Using sealed storage, the song is securely encrypted using a key bound to the trusted platform module so that only the unmodified and untampered music player on his or her computer can play it.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] In this DRM architecture, this might also prevent people from listening to the song after buying a new computer, or upgrading parts of their current one, except after explicit permission of the vendor of the song.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Remote attestation allows changes to the user's computer to be detected by authorized parties.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] For example, software companies can identify unauthorized changes to software, including users modifying their software to circumvent commercial digital rights restrictions.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] It works by having the hardware generate a certificate stating what software is currently running.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The computer can then present this certificate to a remote party to show that unaltered software is currently executing.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Numerous remote attestation schemes have been proposed for various computer architectures, including Intel, RISC-V, and ARM.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Remote attestation is usually combined with public-key encryption so that the information sent can only be read by the programs that requested the attestation, and not by an eavesdropper.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] To take the song example again, the user's music player software could send the song to other machines, but only if they could attest that they were running an authorized copy of the music player software.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] To preserve the privacy of attestation responders, Direct Anonymous Attestation has been proposed as a solution, which uses a group signature scheme to prevent revealing the identity of individual signers.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Proof of space (PoS) have been proposed to be used for malware detection, by determining whether the L1 cache of a processor is empty (e.g., has enough space to evaluate the PoSpace routine without cache misses) or contains a routine that resisted being evicted.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The Microsoft products Windows Vista, Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows RT make use of a Trusted Platform Module to facilitate BitLocker Drive Encryption.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Other known applications with runtime encryption and the use of secure enclaves include the Signal messenger and the e-prescription service ("E-Rezept") by the German government.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing would allow companies to create a digital rights management (DRM) system which would be very hard to circumvent, though not impossible.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Sealed storage could be used to prevent the user from opening the file with an unauthorized player or computer.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Remote attestation could be used to authorize play only by music players that enforce the record company's rules.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The music would be played from curtained memory, which would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure I/O would prevent capturing what is being sent to the sound system.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Circumventing such a system would require either manipulation of the computer's hardware, capturing the analogue (and thus degraded) signal using a recording device or a microphone, or breaking the security of the system.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] New business models for use of software (services) over Internet may be boosted by the technology.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] By strengthening the DRM system, one could base a business model on renting programs for a specific time periods or "pay as you go" models.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] For instance, one could download a music file which could only be played a certain number of times before it becomes unusable, or the music file could be used only within a certain time period.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing could be used to combat cheating in online games.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Some players modify their game copy in order to gain unfair advantages in the game; remote attestation, secure I/O and memory curtaining could be used to determine that all players connected to a server were running an unmodified copy of the software.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing could be used to guarantee participants in a grid computing system are returning the results of the computations they claim to be instead of forging them.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] This would allow large scale simulations to be run (say a climate simulation) without expensive redundant computations to guarantee malicious hosts are not undermining the results to achieve the conclusion they want.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Free Software Foundation criticize that trust in the underlying companies is not deserved and that the technology puts too much power and control into the hands of those who design systems and software.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] They also state that it may cause consumers to lose anonymity in their online interactions, as well as mandating technologies Trusted Computing opponents say are unnecessary.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] They suggest Trusted Computing as a possible enabler for future versions of mandatory access control, copy protection, and DRM.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Some security experts, such as Alan Cox and Bruce Schneier, have spoken out against Trusted Computing, believing it will provide computer manufacturers and software authors with increased control to impose restrictions on what users are able to do with their computers.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] There are concerns that Trusted Computing would have an anti-competitive effect on the IT market.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] There is concern amongst critics that it will not always be possible to examine the hardware components on which Trusted Computing relies, the Trusted Platform Module, which is the ultimate hardware system where the core 'root' of trust in the platform has to reside.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] If not implemented correctly, it presents a security risk to overall platform integrity and protected data.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The specifications, as published by the Trusted Computing Group, are open and are available for anyone to review.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] However, the final implementations by commercial vendors will not necessarily be subjected to the same review process.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] In addition, the world of cryptography can often move quickly, and that hardware implementations of algorithms might create an inadvertent obsolescence.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Trusting networked computers to controlling authorities rather than to individuals may create digital imprimaturs.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] One of the early motivations behind trusted computing was a desire by media and software corporations for stricter DRM technology to prevent users from freely sharing and using potentially copyrighted or private files without explicit permission.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] An example could be downloading a music file from a band: the band's record company could come up with rules for how the band's music can be used.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] For example, they might want the user to play the file only three times a day without paying additional money.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Also, they could use remote attestation to only send their music to a music player that enforces their rules: sealed storage would prevent the user from opening the file with another player that did not enforce the restrictions.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Memory curtaining would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure output would prevent capturing what is sent to the sound system.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] A user who wanted to switch to a competing program might find that it would be impossible for that new program to read old data, as the information would be "locked in" to the old program.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] It could also make it impossible for the user to read or modify their data except as specifically permitted by the software.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The law in many countries allows users certain rights over data whose copyright they do not own (including text, images, and other media), often under headings such as fair use or public interest.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Depending on jurisdiction, these may cover issues such as whistleblowing, production of evidence in court, quoting or other small-scale usage, backups of owned media, and making a copy of owned material for personal use on other owned devices or systems.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The steps implicit in trusted computing have the practical effect of preventing users exercising these legal rights.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] A service that requires external validation or permission - such as a music file or game that requires connection with the vendor to confirm permission to play or use - is vulnerable to that service being withdrawn or no longer updated.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] A number of incidents have already occurred where users, having purchased music or video media, have found their ability to watch or listen to it suddenly stop due to vendor policy or cessation of service, or server inaccessibility, at times with no compensation.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Alternatively in some cases the vendor refuses to provide services in future which leaves purchased material only usable on the present -and increasingly obsolete- hardware (so long as it lasts) but not on any hardware that may be purchased in future.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Some opponents of Trusted Computing advocate "owner override": allowing an owner who is confirmed to be physically present to allow the computer to bypass restrictions and use the secure I/O path.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Such an override would allow remote attestation to a user's specification, e.g., to create certificates that say Internet Explorer is running, even if a different browser is used.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Instead of preventing software change, remote attestation would indicate when the software has been changed without owner's permission.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing Group members have refused to implement owner override.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Proponents of trusted computing believe that owner override defeats the trust in other computers since remote attestation can be forged by the owner.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Owner override offers the security and enforcement benefits to a machine owner, but does not allow them to trust other computers, because their owners could waive rules or restrictions on their own computers.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Under this scenario, once data is sent to someone else's computer, whether it be a diary, a DRM music file, or a joint project, that other person controls what security, if any, their computer will enforce on their copy of those data.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] This has the potential to undermine the applications of trusted computing to enforce DRM, control cheating in online games and attest to remote computations for grid computing.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Because a Trusted Computing equipped computer is able to uniquely attest to its own identity, it will be possible for vendors and others who possess the ability to use the attestation feature to zero in on the identity of the user of TC-enabled software with a high degree of certainty.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Such a capability is contingent on the reasonable chance that the user at some time provides user-identifying information, whether voluntarily, indirectly, or simply through inference of many seemingly benign pieces of data.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] (e.g. search records, as shown through simple study of the AOL search records leak).
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] One common way that information can be obtained and linked is when a user registers a computer just after purchase.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Another common way is when a user provides identifying information to the website of an affiliate of the vendor.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] While proponents of TC point out that online purchases and credit transactions could potentially be more secure as a result of the remote attestation capability, this may cause the computer user to lose expectations of anonymity when using the Internet.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Critics point out that this could have a chilling effect on political free speech, the ability of journalists to use anonymous sources, whistle blowing, political blogging and other areas where the public needs protection from retaliation through anonymity.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The TPM specification offers features and suggested implementations that are meant to address the anonymity requirement.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] By using a third-party Privacy Certification Authority (PCA), the information that identifies the computer could be held by a trusted third party.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Additionally, the use of direct anonymous attestation (DAA), introduced in TPM v1.2, allows a client to perform attestation while not revealing any personally identifiable or machine information.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The kind of data that must be supplied to the TTP in order to get the trusted status is at present not entirely clear, but the TCG itself admits that "attestation is an important TPM function with significant privacy implications".
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] It is, however, clear that both static and dynamic information about the user computer may be supplied (Ekpubkey) to the TTP (v1.1b), it is not clear what data will be supplied to the “verifier” under v1.2.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The static information will uniquely identify the endorser of the platform, model, details of the TPM, and that the platform (PC) complies with the TCG specifications .
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The dynamic information is described as software running on the computer.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] If a program like Windows is registered in the user's name this in turn will uniquely identify the user.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Another dimension of privacy infringing capabilities might also be introduced with this new technology; how often you use your programs might be possible information provided to the TTP.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] In an exceptional, however practical situation, where a user purchases a pornographic movie on the Internet, the purchaser nowadays, must accept the fact that he has to provide credit card details to the provider, thereby possibly risking being identified.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] With the new technology a purchaser might also risk someone finding out that he (or she) has watched this pornographic movie 1000 times.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] This adds a new dimension to the possible privacy infringement.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The extent of data that will be supplied to the TTP/Verifiers is at present not exactly known, only when the technology is implemented and used will we be able to assess the exact nature and volume of the data that is transmitted.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing requests that all software and hardware vendors will follow the technical specifications released by the Trusted Computing Group in order to allow interoperability between different trusted software stacks.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] However, since at least mid-2006, there have been interoperability problems between the TrouSerS trusted software stack (released as open source software by IBM) and Hewlett-Packard's stack.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Another problem is that the technical specifications are still changing, so it is unclear which is the standard implementation of the trusted stack.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] People have voiced concerns that trusted computing could be used to keep or discourage users from running software created by companies outside of a small industry group.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The concerns about trusted computing being used to shut out competition exist within a broader framework of consumers being concerned about using bundling of products to obscure prices of products and to engage in anti-competitive practices.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing is seen as harmful or problematic to independent and open source software developers.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] In the widely used public-key cryptography, creation of keys can be done on the local computer and the creator has complete control over who has access to it, and consequentially their own security policies.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] In some proposed encryption-decryption chips, a private/public key is permanently embedded into the hardware when it is manufactured, and hardware manufacturers would have the opportunity to record the key without leaving evidence of doing so.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] With this key it would be possible to have access to data encrypted with it, and to authenticate as it.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] It is trivial for a manufacturer to give a copy of this key to the government or the software manufacturers, as the platform must go through steps so that it works with authenticated software.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] A security breach breaking that chain of trust happened to a SIM card manufacturer Gemalto, which in 2010 was infiltrated by US and British spies, resulting in compromised security of cellphone calls.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] It is also critical that one be able to trust that the hardware manufacturers and software developers properly implement trusted computing standards.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Incorrect implementation could be hidden from users, and thus could undermine the integrity of the whole system without users being aware of the flaw.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Since 2004, most major manufacturers have shipped systems that have included Trusted Platform Modules, with associated BIOS support.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] In accordance with the TCG specifications, the user must enable the Trusted Platform Module before it can be used.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Processor manufacturers have included secure enclaves in their design such as ARM TrustZone, Intel Management Engine with SGX and AMD PSP with Secure Encrypted Virtualization.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The Linux kernel has included trusted computing support since version 2.6.13, and there are several projects to implement trusted computing for Linux.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] In January 2005, members of Gentoo Linux's "crypto herd" announced their intention of providing support for TC—in particular support for the Trusted Platform Module.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] There is also a TCG-compliant software stack for Linux named TrouSerS, released under an open source license.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] There are several open-source projects that facilitate the use of confidential computing technology, including EGo, EdgelessDB and MarbleRun from Edgeless Systems, as well as Enarx, which originates from security research at Red Hat.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Some limited form of trusted computing can be implemented on current versions of Microsoft Windows with third-party software.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Major cloud providers such as Microsoft Azure, AWS and Google Cloud Platform have virtual machines with trusted computing features available.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] The Intel Classmate PC (a competitor to the One Laptop Per Child) includes a Trusted Platform Module.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] PrivateCore vCage software can be used to attest x86 servers with TPM chips.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Google enforces Play Integrity API to Android devices with their bootloader unlocked.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Mobile T6 secure operating system simulates the TPM functionality in mobile devices using the ARM TrustZone technology.
[src:tpm-module/remote-attestation] Samsung smartphones come equipped with Samsung Knox that depend on features like Secure Boot, TIMA, MDM, TrustZone and SE Linux.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A **secure cryptoprocessor** is a dedicated computer-on-a-chip or microprocessor for carrying out cryptographic operations, embedded in a packaging with multiple physical security measures, which give it a degree of tamper resistance.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Unlike cryptographic processors that output decrypted data onto a bus in a secure environment, a secure cryptoprocessor does not output decrypted data or decrypted program instructions in an environment where security cannot always be maintained.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The purpose of a secure cryptoprocessor is to act as the keystone of a security subsystem, eliminating the need to protect the rest of the subsystem with physical security measures.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module (HSM) contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] These devices are high grade secure cryptoprocessors used with enterprise servers.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module can have multiple levels of physical security with a single-chip cryptoprocessor as its most secure component.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The cryptoprocessor does not reveal keys or executable instructions on a bus, except in encrypted form, and zeros keys by attempts at probing or scanning.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The crypto chip(s) may also be potted in the hardware security module with other processors and memory chips that store and process encrypted data.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Any attempt to remove the potting will cause the keys in the crypto chip to be zeroed.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module may also be part of a computer (for example an ATM) that operates inside a locked safe to deter theft, substitution, and tampering.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Some secure cryptoprocessors can even run general-purpose operating systems such as Linux inside their security boundary.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Cryptoprocessors input program instructions in encrypted form and decrypt the instructions to plain instructions, which are then executed within the same cryptoprocessor chip where the decrypted instructions are inaccessibly stored.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] By never revealing the decrypted program instructions, the cryptoprocessor prevents tampering of programs by technicians who may have legitimate access to the sub-system data bus.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Data processed by a cryptoprocessor is also frequently encrypted.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is an implementation of a secure cryptoprocessor that brings the notion of trusted computing to ordinary PCs by enabling a secure environment.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Present TPM implementations focus on providing a tamper-proof boot environment, and persistent and volatile storage encryption.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Security chips for embedded systems are also available that provide the same level of physical protection for keys and other secret material as a smartcard processor or TPM but in a smaller, less complex and less expensive package.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] They are often referred to as cryptographic authentication devices and are used to authenticate peripherals, accessories and/or consumables.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Like TPMs, they are usually turnkey integrated circuits intended to be embedded in a system, usually soldered to a PC board.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Secure cryptoprocessors, while useful, are not invulnerable to attack, particularly for well-equipped and determined opponents (e.g. a government intelligence agency) who are willing to expend enough resources on the project.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] One attack on a secure cryptoprocessor targeted the IBM 4758.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A team at the University of Cambridge reported the successful extraction of secret information from an IBM 4758, using a combination of mathematics, and special-purpose codebreaking hardware.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] However, this attack was not practical in real-world systems because it required the attacker to have full access to all API functions of the device.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Normal and recommended practices use the integral access control system to split authority so that no one person could mount the attack.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Smartcards are significantly more vulnerable, as they are more open to physical attack.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Additionally, hardware backdoors can undermine security in smartcards and other cryptoprocessors unless investment is made in anti-backdoor design methods.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] This would require both physical possession of the device as well as skills and equipment beyond that of most technical personnel.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Other attack methods involve carefully analyzing the timing of various operations that might vary depending on the secret value or mapping the current consumption versus time to identify differences in the way that '0' bits are handled internally vs.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Or the attacker may apply temperature extremes, excessively high or low clock frequencies or supply voltage that exceeds the specifications in order to induce a fault.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The internal design of the cryptoprocessor can be tailored to prevent these attacks.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The first single-chip cryptoprocessor design was for copy protection of personal computer software (see US Patent 4,168,396, Sept 18, 1979) and was inspired by Bill Gates's Open Letter to Hobbyists.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The hardware security module (HSM), a type of secure cryptoprocessor, was invented by Egyptian-American engineer Mohamed M.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] He invented a high security module dubbed the "Atalla Box" which encrypted PIN and ATM messages, and protected offline devices with an un-guessable PIN-generating key.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] In 1972, he filed a patent for the device.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] He founded Atalla Corporation (now Utimaco Atalla) that year, and commercialized the "Atalla Box" the following year, officially as the Identikey system.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was a card reader and customer identification system, consisting of a card reader console, two customer PIN pads, intelligent controller and built-in electronic interface package.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It allowed the customer to type in a secret code, which is transformed by the device, using a microprocessor, into another code for the teller.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] During a transaction, the customer's account number was read by the card reader.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was a success, and led to the wide use of high security modules.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Fearful that Atalla would dominate the market, banks and credit card companies began working on an international standard in the 1970s.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The IBM 3624, launched in the late 1970s, adopted a similar PIN verification process to the earlier Atalla system.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Atalla was an early competitor to IBM in the banking security market.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] At the National Association of Mutual Savings Banks (NAMSB) conference in January 1976, Atalla unveiled an upgrade to its Identikey system, called the Interchange Identikey.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It added the capabilities of processing online transactions and dealing with network security.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Designed with the focus of taking bank transactions online, the Identikey system was extended to shared-facility operations.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was consistent and compatible with various switching networks, and was capable of resetting itself electronically to any one of 64,000 irreversible nonlinear algorithms as directed by card data information.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The Interchange Identikey device was released in March 1976.
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Later in 1979, Atalla introduced the first network security processor (NSP).
[src:tpm-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Atalla's HSM products protect 250 million card transactions every day as of 2013, and secure the majority of the world's ATM transactions as of 2014.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper resistance ranges from simple features like screws with special drives and tamper-evident seals to more complex devices that render themselves inoperable or encrypt all data transmissions between individual chips, use of materials needing special tools and knowledge.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant devices or features are common on packages to deter package or product tampering or enable its detection.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Anti-tamper devices have one or more components: tamper resistance, tamper detection, tamper response, and tamper evidence.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] In some applications, devices are only tamper-evident rather than tamper-resistant.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tampering involves the deliberate altering or adulteration of a product, package, or system.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Solutions may involve all phases of product production, packaging, distribution, logistics, sale, and use.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] No single solution can be considered as "tamper-proof".
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Often multiple levels of security need to be addressed to reduce the risk of tampering.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Some devices contain non-standard screws or bolts in an attempt to deter access.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Examples are telephone switching cabinets (which have triangular bolt heads that a hex socket fits), or bolts with 5-sided heads used to secure doors to outdoor electrical distribution transformers.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] A standard Torx screw head can be made in a tamper-resistant form with a pin in the center, which excludes standard Torx drivers.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Various other security screw heads have been devised to discourage casual access to the interior of such devices as consumer electronics.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] This style of tamper resistance is most commonly found in burglar alarms.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Most trip devices (e.g. pressure pads, passive infrared sensors (motion detectors), door switches) use two signal wires that, depending on configuration, are normally open or normally closed.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] The sensors sometimes need power, so to simplify cable runs, multi-core cable is used.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] While 4 cores is normally enough for devices that require power (leaving two spare for those that don't), cable with additional cores can be used.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] These additional cores can be wired into a special so-called "tamper circuit" in the alarm system.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper circuits are monitored by the system to give an alarm if a disturbance to devices or wiring is detected.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Enclosures for devices and control panels may be fitted with anti-tamper switches.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Would-be intruders run the risk of triggering the alarm by attempting to circumvent a given device.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Sensors such as movement detectors, tilt detectors, air-pressure sensors, light sensors, etc., which might be employed in some burglar alarms, might also be used in a bomb to hinder defusing.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Nearly all appliances and accessories can only be opened with the use of a tool.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] This is intended to prevent casual or accidental access to energized or hot parts, or damage to the equipment.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Manufacturers may use tamper-resistant screws, which cannot be unfastened with common tools.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant screws are used on electrical fittings in many public buildings to reduce tampering or vandalism that may cause a danger to others.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] A user who breaks equipment by modifying it in a way not intended by the manufacturer might deny they did it, in order to claim the warranty or (mainly in the case of PCs) call the helpdesk for help in fixing it.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-evident seals may be enough to deal with this.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] However, they cannot easily be checked remotely, and many countries have statutory warranty terms that mean manufacturers may still have to service the equipment.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper proof screws will stop most casual users from tampering in the first place.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] In the US, the Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act prevents manufacturers from voiding warranties solely due to tampering.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] A warranty may be dishonored only if the tampering actually affected the part that has failed, and could have caused the failure.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant microprocessors are used to store and process private or sensitive information, such as private keys or electronic money credit.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] To prevent an attacker from retrieving or modifying the information, the chips are designed so that the information is not accessible through external means and can be accessed only by the embedded software, which should contain the appropriate security measures.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Examples of tamper-resistant chips include all secure cryptoprocessors, such as the IBM 4758 and chips used in smartcards, as well as the Clipper chip.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant chips may be designed to zeroise their sensitive data (especially cryptographic keys) if they detect penetration of their security encapsulation or out-of-specification environmental parameters.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] A chip may even be rated for "cold zeroisation", the ability to zeroise itself even after its power supply has been crippled.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] In addition, the custom-made encapsulation methods used for chips used in some cryptographic products may be designed in such a manner that they are internally pre-stressed, so the chip will fracture if interfered with.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Nevertheless, the fact that an attacker may have the device in their possession for as long as they like, and perhaps obtain numerous other samples for testing and practice, means that it is impossible to totally eliminate tampering by a sufficiently motivated opponent.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Because of this, one of the most important elements in protecting a system is overall system design.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] In particular, tamper-resistant systems should "fail gracefully" by ensuring that compromise of one device does not compromise the entire system.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] In this manner, the attacker can be practically restricted to attacks that cost more than the expected return from compromising a single device.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Since the most sophisticated attacks have been estimated to cost several hundred thousand dollars to carry out, carefully designed systems may be invulnerable in practice.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] In the United States, purchasing specifications require anti-tamper (AT) features on military electronic systems.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper resistance finds application in smart cards, set-top boxes and other devices that use digital rights management (DRM).
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] In this case, the issue is not about stopping the user from breaking the equipment or hurting themselves, but about either stopping them from extracting codes, or acquiring and saving the decoded bitstream.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] This is usually done by having many subsystem features buried within each chip (so that internal signals and states are inaccessible) and by making sure the buses between chips are encrypted.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] DRM mechanisms also use certificates and asymmetric key cryptography in many cases.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] In all such cases, tamper resistance means not allowing the device user access to the valid device certificates or public-private keys of the device.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] The process of making software robust against tampering attacks is referred to as "software anti-tamper".
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Resistance to tampering can be built in or added to packaging.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] Software is also said to be tamper-resistant when it contains measures to make reverse engineering harder, or to prevent a user from modifying it against the manufacturer's wishes (such as removing a restriction on how it can be used).
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] One commonly used method is code obfuscation.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] However, effective tamper resistance in software is much harder than in hardware, as the software environment can be manipulated to near-arbitrary extent by the use of emulation.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] If implemented, trusted computing would make software tampering of protected programs at least as difficult as hardware tampering, as the user would have to hack the trust chip to give false certifications in order to bypass remote attestation and sealed storage.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] However, the current specification makes it clear that the chip is not expected to be tamper-proof against any reasonably sophisticated physical attack; that is, it is not intended to be as secure as a tamper-resistant device.
[src:tpm-module/tamper-resistance] That has the side effect that software maintenance gets more complex because software updates need to be validated, and errors in the upgrade process may lead to a false-positive triggering of the protection mechanism.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] A **Trusted Platform Module** (**TPM**) is a secure cryptoprocessor that implements the **ISO/IEC 11889** standard.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Common uses are verifying that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software and storing disk encryption keys.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] A TPM 2.0 implementation is part of the Windows 11 system requirements.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The first TPM version that was deployed was 1.1b in 2003.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) was conceived by a computer industry consortium called Trusted Computing Group (TCG).
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It evolved into *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* which was standardized by International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in 2009 as ISO/IEC 11889:2009.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* was finalized on 3 March 2011 completing its revision.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] On April 9, 2014, the Trusted Computing Group announced a major upgrade to their specification entitled *TPM Library Specification 2.0*.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The group continues work on the standard incorporating errata, algorithmic additions and new commands, with its most recent edition published as 2.0 in November 2019.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] When a new revision is released, it is divided into multiple parts by the Trusted Computing Group.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Each part consists of a document that makes up the whole of the new TPM specification.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] While TPM 2.0 addresses many of the same use cases and has similar features, the details are different.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] TPM 2.0 is not backward compatible with TPM 1.2.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The TPM 2.0 policy authorization includes the 1.2 HMAC, locality, physical presence, and PCR.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It adds authorization based on an asymmetric digital signature, indirection to another authorization secret, counters and time limits, NVRAM values, a particular command or command parameters, and physical presence.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It permits the ANDing and ORing of these authorization primitives to construct complex authorization policies.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Computer programs can use a TPM for the authentication of hardware devices, since each TPM chip has a unique and secret Endorsement Key (EK) burned in as it is produced.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Security embedded in hardware provides more protection than a software-only solution.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Its use is restricted in some countries.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The primary scope of TPM is to ensure the integrity of a platform during boot time.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In this context, "integrity" means "behaves as intended", and a "platform" is any computer device regardless of its operating system.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] This is to ensure that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software, and continues until the operating system has fully booted and applications are running.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] When TPM is used, the firmware and the operating system are responsible for ensuring integrity.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] For example, the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) can use TPM to form a root of trust: The TPM contains several Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) that allow secure storage and reporting of security-relevant metrics.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] These metrics can be used to detect changes to previous configurations and decide how to proceed.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Examples of such use can be found in Linux Unified Key Setup (LUKS), BitLocker and PrivateCore vCage memory encryption.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Another example of platform integrity via TPM is in the use of Microsoft Office 365 licensing and Outlook Exchange.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Another example of TPM use for platform integrity is the Trusted Execution Technology (TXT), which creates a chain of trust.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It could remotely attest that a computer is using the specified hardware and software.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Full disk encryption utilities, such as dm-crypt, can use this technology to protect the keys used to encrypt the computer's storage devices and provide integrity authentication for a trusted boot pathway that includes firmware and the boot sector.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2006, new laptops began being sold with a built-in TPM chip.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In the future, this concept could be co-located on an existing motherboard chip in computers, or any other device where the TPM facilities could be employed, such as a cellphone.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] On a PC, either the Low Pin Count (LPC) bus or the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI) bus is used to connect to the TPM chip.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The official TCG reference implementation of the TPM 2.0 Specification has been developed by Microsoft.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It is licensed under BSD License and the source code is available on GitHub.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, Intel open-sourced its Trusted Platform Module 2.0 (TPM2) software stack with support for Linux and Microsoft Windows.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Infineon funded the development of an open source TPM middleware that complies with the Software Stack (TSS) Enhanced System API (ESAPI) specification of the TCG.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It was developed by Fraunhofer Institute for Secure Information Technology (SIT).
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] IBM's Software TPM 2.0 is an implementation of the TCG TPM 2.0 specification.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It is based on the TPM specification Parts 3 and 4 and source code donated by Microsoft.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It contains additional files to complete the implementation.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on SourceForge and GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2022, AMD announced that under certain circumstances their fTPM implementation causes performance problems.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] A fix is available in form of a BIOS-Update.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The Trusted Computing Group (TCG) has faced resistance to the deployment of this technology in some areas, where some authors see possible uses not specifically related to Trusted Computing, which may raise privacy concerns.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The concerns include the abuse of remote validation of software to decide what software is allowed to run, and possible ways to follow actions taken by the user and record them in a database in a manner that is completely undetectable to the user.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The TrueCrypt disk encryption utility, as well as its derivative VeraCrypt, do not support TPM.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The original TrueCrypt developers were of the opinion that the exclusive purpose of the TPM is "to protect against attacks that require the attacker to have administrator privileges, or physical access to the computer".
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The attacker who has physical or administrative access to a computer can circumvent TPM, e.g., by installing a hardware keystroke logger, by resetting TPM, or by capturing memory contents and retrieving TPM-issued keys.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The condemning text goes so far as to claim that TPM is entirely redundant.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The VeraCrypt publisher has reproduced the original allegation with no changes other than replacing "TrueCrypt" with "VeraCrypt".
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The author is right that, after achieving either unrestricted physical access or administrative privileges, it is only a matter of time before other security measures in place are bypassed.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] However, stopping an attacker in possession of administrative privileges has never been one of the goals of TPM (see § Uses for details), and TPM can stop some physical tampering.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, Richard Stallman suggested replacing the term "trusted computing" with the term "treacherous computing" due to the danger that the computer can be made to systematically disobey its owner if the cryptographical keys are kept secret from them.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In August 2023, Linus Torvalds, who was frustrated with AMD fTPM's stuttering bugs, opined, "Let's just disable the stupid fTPM `hwrnd` thing." He said the CPU-based random number generation, `rdrand`, was equally suitable, despite having its share of bugs.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2010, Christopher Tarnovsky presented an attack against TPMs at Black Hat Briefings, where he claimed to be able to extract secrets from a single TPM.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] He was able to do this after 6 months of work by inserting a probe and spying on an internal bus for the Infineon SLE 66 CL PC.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In case of physical access, computers with TPM 1.2 are vulnerable to cold boot attacks as long as the system is on or can be booted without a passphrase from shutdown, sleep or hibernation, which is the default setup for Windows computers with BitLocker full disk encryption.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] A fix was proposed, which has been adopted in the specifications for TPM 2.0.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2009, the concept of shared authorisation data in TPM 1.2 was found to be flawed.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] An adversary given access to the data could spoof responses from the TPM.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, as part of the Snowden revelations, it was revealed that in 2010 a US CIA team claimed at an internal conference to have carried out a differential power analysis attack against TPMs that was able to extract secrets.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Main Trusted Boot (tboot) distributions before November 2017 are affected by a dynamic root of trust for measurement (DRTM) attack CVE-2017-16837, which affects computers running on Intel's Trusted eXecution Technology (TXT) for the boot-up routine.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In October 2017, it was reported that a code library developed by Infineon, which had been in widespread use in its TPMs, contained a vulnerability, known as ROCA, which generated weak RSA key pairs that allowed private keys to be inferred from public keys.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] As a result, all systems depending upon the privacy of such weak keys are vulnerable to compromise, such as identity theft or spoofing.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Cryptosystems that store encryption keys directly in the TPM without blinding could be at particular risk to these types of attacks, as passwords and other factors would be meaningless if the attacks can extract encryption secrets.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Infineon has released firmware updates for its TPMs to manufacturers who have used them.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, a design flaw in the TPM 2.0 specification for the static root of trust for measurement (SRTM) was reported (CVE-2018-6622).
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] It allows an adversary to reset and forge platform configuration registers which are designed to securely hold measurements of software that are used for bootstrapping a computer.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Fixing it requires hardware-specific firmware patches.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] An attacker abuses power interrupts and TPM state restores to trick TPM into thinking that it is running on non-tampered components.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] In 2021, the Dolos Group showed an attack on a discrete TPM, where the TPM chip itself had some tamper resistance, but the other endpoints of its communication bus did not.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] They read a full-disk-encryption key as it was transmitted across the motherboard, and used it to decrypt the laptop's SSD.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] As of 2025, a TPM is provided by nearly all PC and notebook manufacturers in their products.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] There are also hybrid types; for example, TPM can be integrated into an Ethernet controller, thus eliminating the need for a separate motherboard component.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Field upgrade is the TCG term for updating the TPM firmware.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The update can be between TPM 1.2 and TPM 2.0, or between firmware versions.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Some vendors limit the number of transitions between 1.2 and 2.0, and some restrict rollback to previous versions.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Platform OEMs such as HP supply an upgrade tool.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Since July 28, 2016, all new Microsoft device models, lines, or series (or updating the hardware configuration of an existing model, line, or series with a major update, such as CPU, graphic cards) implement, and enable by default TPM 2.0.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] TPM endorsement keys (EKs) are asymmetric key pairs unique to each TPM.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The TPM manufacturer usually provisions endorsement key certificates in TPM non-volatile memory.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The certificates assert that the TPM is authentic.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Starting with TPM 2.0, the certificates are in X.509 DER format.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] After the TPM was manufactured, the EKs cannot be changed.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] For fTPM, the EKs are stored on CPU / chipset when it was manufactured.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] These manufacturers typically provide their certificate authority root (and sometimes intermediate) certificates on their web sites.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] To utilize a TPM, the user needs a software library that communicates with the TPM and provides a friendlier API than the raw TPM communication.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Currently, there are several such open-source TPM 2.0 libraries.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Some of them also support TPM 1.2, but mostly TPM 1.2 chips are now deprecated and modern development is focused on TPM 2.0.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Typically, a TPM library provides an API with one-to-one mappings to TPM commands.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification calls this layer the System API (SAPI).
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] This way, the user has more control over the TPM operations, but the complexity is high.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] To hide some of the complexity, most libraries also offer simpler ways to invoke complex TPM operations.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification call these two layers Enhanced System API (ESAPI) and Feature API (FAPI).
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] There is currently only one stack that follows the TCG specification.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] All the other available open-source TPM libraries use their own form of richer API.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] There is an application note about an example project for the AURIX 32-bit SoC using the tpm2-tss library.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] Requires additional libraries (dotnet) to run on Linux.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] These TPM libraries are sometimes also called TPM stacks, because they provide the interface for the developer or user to interact with the TPM.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] As seen from the table, the TPM stacks abstract the operating system and transport layer, so the user could migrate one application between platforms.
[src:tpm-module/trusted-platform-module] For example, by using TPM stack API the user would interact the same way with a TPM, regardless if the physical chip is connected over SPI, I2C or LPC interface to the Host system.
